5 Firstly, the outside of this is completely invisible. It's just a seemingly random building that nobody glances at. Inside is this extremely nice restaurant. Too nice for Chinatown, I think. I was shocked. Two-story-high ceilings, everything is in perfect condition, beyond the "western" standards. I mean, you know how it usually is in most Chinatown spots - they're kept running at bare minimum cleanliness so nobody notices.  Anyway. The food. Browsing the menu, I've seldom seen so many hilarious typos and oddities. Gems include:  - Crap and pork dumplings - A mixed pot of miscellaneous - Abgus beed - Fried tofu with brown sauce  Appetizing. Anyway we stuck with (over a few visits):  Shanghai style fried rice cakes: this is my newly acquired favorite. Not everyone can pull this off and I think it's due to the quality of rice cake and then the way it is cooked. Theirs is perfect. Soft rice cake that almost breaks apart with a little pressure. Flavors right, with the crunch of the cabbage and leafy greens. Loved it.  Fried taro sticks: imagine taro fries with a lot of salt and even more pepper. We didn't expect this. We expected something a little bit on the neutral/sweet side. Did not like.  Hot and sour soup: It's what you expect, with extra sourness. Nothing noteworthy. Not bad, but not memorable.  Pork dumplings: Yes. Get these. If these are any indication of the rest of their dumplings then this is my favorite dumpling spot in Vegas, easily. They were filled with delicious soup, quality ground pork, and all the flavors were just right. I loved these. I wanted more but I knew I still had to eat....  Pan fried pork buns: Yes. Yes yes yes yes. Absolutely get these. Steamed pork buns with the perfect pan frying on the bottom. I don't know how they got it so perfect but it's very crunchy on the bottom, a little crispy on the sides, and soft steamed bun goodness on top. Inside is pork with soup like the dumplings. It's amazing. Seriously.  Tofu and vegetables in a clay pot. Could a menu item be more descriptive? Only if it named suppliers. This is exactly what it sounds like, in a lightly sweet sauce. It stays hot for a long time so please don't burn yourself as many tunes as times as I did.  Eggplant with tofu. I think they cooked the eggplant just right. They left some firmness in. But the sauce was too much and could probably be cut in half. Still, I love eggplant and this was a must.  Rice cake sesame balls: These were served in a bowl with a very subtly sweet water. The water is nothing to speak of, but we suspected the balls were made in-house. The sesame paste inside was very tasty. These were really fun to eat.  Papaya... pastry?: Basically, puff pastry with papaya filling. Essentially a papaya turnover. This could not be bad, and it wasn't. It's exactly what you'd expect.  Service was timely, and prices were very reasonable for the quality we got. I loved most of what we had and I'd definitely be back. I liked another detail often overlooked - the tea pots. They had the end of the spouts curved to fit a teacup underneath, and pour perfectly almost without lifting much without any spills. I was wowed. Yes, sometimes I'm easily amused but hey, in all my years experiencing Asian cuisine, this has never happened. Oh yeah, tea was good.
